<TITLE> Japan begin search for Osim's successor </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TOKYO, Nov 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Japan will soon begin searching for a replacement for national coach Ivica Osim with the Bosnian still in a coma after suffering a stroke. "We do have the issue of who will the next coach of the national side to think about," Japan Football Association (JFA) technical director Kozo Tajima told reporters. Osim, 66, has been in an intensive care unit since he collapsed at his home in Chiba, near Tokyo, on Nov. 16 while climbing the stairs. The outspoken Bosnian took over from Brazilian Zico after Japan's meek exit from the 2006 World Cup but began showing signs of stress at the Asian Cup this year. Japan begin their 2010 World Cup qualifying campaign in February and JFA president Saburo Kawabuchi has said he wants to find a new coach as quickly as possible. Kawabuchi also denied the JFA were lining up Urawa Reds' German coach Holger Osieck as Osim's replacement
